commentText: I've lived in Florida since the early 1960's. Florida used to be quite  cheap compared to most metropolitan areas in the country. Over the last  20-30 years, real estate prices in the better coastal cities (and  Orlando) have increased dramatically. My mother bought us, our first  home in a hip area of Ft. Lauderdale, back in 1964, for $11,000. Today,  that same home (renovated) and 2 blocks away from extravagant Las Olas  Blvd. (if you know Ft. Lauderdale) is now worth over $850,000.   I purchased my first home in Sarasota back in 1988. It's was a Florida  Craftsman Bungalow style, and I paid $41,000. Today, that home is worth  about $300,000, but only because it is in a gentrifying area near  downtown Sarasota. Those are extreme examples, but I have seen real  estate prices triple here in Sarasota, for most homes since the 1980's.  As more people relocate to the more sought-after areas of Florida, it  has pushed the prices of real estate to almost un-affordable levels for  the working class folks. In Sarasota, just a basic home will cost $200k  minimum. If you go south to North Port or Port Charlotte, a basic home  will run about $160k and up. A 2 bedroom apartment in Sarasota for rent  is about $1400/month. It might be lower outside the Sarasota city area,  which tends to run about 20% higher than surrounding communities.  Florida has a lot of service-sector jobs, where $12/hour is about  average. So, unless you make a real professional wage, like $25/hour and  up, (and I mean mostly "up"), then Florida could seem quite expensive.  Probably one of the best industries I can think of to work in Florida,  would be healthcare, with the aging population here. If you are coming   from the major cities of the northeast (N.Y., Boston, Philadelphia),  then prices of homes in Florida will seem reasonable. If you're coming  from "flyover country" in the mid-west, or some small town somewhere,  then Florida will seem expensive. If you're coming from a major city in  California, then Florida will seem like an absolute bargain in  comparison.   If you're retired or nearing retirement, and have owned a home up north  that is now worth $800k to over a million dollars, you can sell that  home, move to Florida, and buy a beautiful home in a gated community for  $400,000+ and live the good life with the money left over, and of  course, never have to shovel snow again. Be prepared for population  growth. It is getting crowded down here now!

commentText: My own experience is as follows. I lived in NY for 26 yrs. Everybody knows how over crowded it is and the crowd is not exactly pleasant. The winters have been BRUTAL, if you drive you will be miserable. I got married and moved into 2 bedroom apartment paying $1425 per month. The second room was the size of a walk in closet. My wife and I made a combined $75k per yr. before taxes. After taxes we were making $52000. We had car payment, ins, utility bills, food, misc. etc. and were managing to save almost $1k per month. I have an ear condition that got progressively worse and the cold weather made it more acute. Combining my health condition and the STRESS of living in NY, I honestly felt that I was going crazy. My quality of life was ZERO. I decided to move to central Florida and my wife and I got jobs with the dept. of Education. It is not the best but we make a combined $3900 per month after taxes. We are currently renting a 4 bedroom 3 bathroom house with beautiful scenery and peaceful environment for $1250, We still pay car, ins, utilities, food, misc, etc. We manage to save the same about 1k per month. We are already planning on purchasing a home. Would I have been able to consider that in NY? NO.  In order for a married couple to purchase a home, they have to make a combined 150k and the house will not compare with what you can get in florida for just 200k. With that said, the quality of life cannot compare to NY. I feel alive here. In NY? dying slowly. I'm not saying that there are pros and cons and that everything has a catch but that is my honest experience so far.

commentText: 2:45 "3 step protection dropped". I think you've misunderstood what three-step protection is. Three-step protection (brakes on, locomotive in neutral, generator field switch off) is used to prevent the train from moving while somebody is working between cars. Three-step was released some time before 2:00 so the train could move. Unless the conductor had to work between the cars again and you didn't show it, three-step would not have been applied again just because the train had stopped beyond the switch.

commentText: I'm glad you finally mentioned the the part about the cost of living later into the video. Yes, getting a "good" job as a self-taught developer is not "easy" down here, but I feel like I lot of people who DO NOT live in Florida unfairly judge the state.  Florida is one of the largest states, has a massive percentage of the US population, and there is no state income tax. There may be no recognized "tech hubs" here but there are a decent amount of people to connect with by going to the many meetups (for various languages and interests) and interacting with the available startups and tech incubators.  Job wise, I'm currently a full-stack developer that works with Vue/Laravel. My first paid job was doing Wordpress and eventually I got my chance to work with more interesting things. When I was still learning Javascript frameworks I started with React because I thought that was in the most demand but I was surprised as during my job hunting process I talked or had interviews with 3 different places down here before getting hired that use Vue (these are probably companies starting relatively newer projects).

videoTitle: At least 920 Florida teachers out of jobs after failing state test, despite 'effective' evaluations
videoDescription: At least 920 Florida teachers just received their pink slips and it's not because they can't teach, but because they can't pass a state ...
commentText: Being a teacher and that has taken the new version of this test, I can say this about the non-subjective sections of the test (which are all of them other than the essay) there is no problem with the academic material that is being tested. However, the time limits you are under for all sections of this test are completely ridiculous. As result from the time limits, if you are not a speed reader with very fast computational skills you will have a very hard time passing.                            As for the essay section I will say multiple problems exist.                                                       1. those that are hired to score the essays are not qualified and are simply following a formula given to them by their employer "Pearson" this formula dictates a score based off writing mechanisms rather than the actual content.  A big one of these would be the number of of transitions used in writing. It seems they are such a high importance that in fact It would most likely be a good idea to interrupt the flow of how the essay reads to include more transitions.                                                                2. Unless you can type over 30 words a minute you will not have enough time to type a passable essay.                                                              3. Considering the subject you will be typing about is completely random (will most likely have nothing to do with teaching or the educational field)and once again time limitations, unless you can type creatively on the fly with proper essay formatting you will not have enough time.  In regards to challenging your test results:                                              1. Don't bother on any of the academic sections (honestly as I said before there is nothing wrong with the questions the test asks as far as I could tell) it is just the limited time issue that is a problem.                                             2. As for the essay section, it can be challenged more successfully as it is subjective. (By their records the chance of successfully challenging is less than 2%)Honestly I failed the essay section 2 times while having passed the others on the first try.  I challenged both times because you are limited in the number of attempts you get to take the test per year.  The first time I challenged my score, I challenged on academic grounds using their own detailed guidelines on how the essay is graded to argue why I should have a better grade. I made more than a good argument and addressed each and every aspect of how the essay was supposedly grade.  The response I received was a cookie cutter letter saying they have decided the score is accurate. No reason given and the long argument I made was not addressed.There was little question after this that challenging a score on academic grounds valid or not was a waste of time.                                                                    3. The second time I took the essay I once again failed it (was not surprised by this as the essay I wrote the first time was better).  As explained above due to the limit on number of times you are allowed to take the test per year I challenged the score again. But this time successfully.  I am not going to give the exact details of how I managed this as it would invite others to use it for dishonest purposes. I will say though the challenge argument I used was based on the program used to give the essay portion of the test.  I pointed out a mechanism in the testing program that was extremely counter intuitive to the typical person and such cause unintended and unknown errors in what was typed by me the writer. I explained why the mechanism was not an excepted or expected occurrence and mentioned that no other word processing program in use whether it be a widely used program or not has such a mechanism.  I cited specific areas in my typed essay that suffered as result of the above mentioned mechanism.  As result of my argument based on the design of the testing program I received a letter about 7 weeks later simply saying that my test had been reviewed and it had been found that it may qualify for adjustment.  It did not say if the adjustment would mean I would now have a passing score which prompted a phone call to the FTCE customer service line.  When I spoke with the women on the phone she confirmed that the score had been changed to a PASS and she also mentioned I was the first person she ever talked to that managed to win a score verification challenge.  So in short if you plan on challenging your test results you will have to write a extremely detailed argument essay that in itself would easily pass if being scored (this time you should have a good idea what you will be typing about beforehand).  Challenging your score based on academics is futile and the only chance you have to succeed is to attack how the test is being given.                                                                                         So as for the question should the test be changed and how.The answer is yes, but the content of the test is just fine.  I also do not believe that the government throwing money at people or paying for test retakes will serve well.                 Change the following:                                  1. The amount of time given on all sections should be increased a good amount.  Really the test should be about if you can answer the questions effectively not a test of speed.                                                    2. If you pay to challenge your test score you should receive and retain detailed report showing why you did not pass especially on subjective sections.  This report should be detailed enough that a person would easily became to understand what they need to work on/learn in order to pass the test the next time.                                                       3.  Especially for the subjective area of the test (essay section) another company that has no conflicts of interests should be used to grade the test.   Honestly it is in the interest of "Pearson" for you to fail the test, so having them grade the test especially the sections where they will be grade subjectively is a conflict of interest that should not exist.

commentText: Reporting is one sided. Where are the teachers who passed? What are their thoughts? I would encourage everyone to do a sample FTCE Math test before casting judgement, whether for or against. I did a sample SAE for another subject and I feel that the test was fair. You definitely have to study a bit and its not going to be 3 x 5 = 15 kind of stuff but then again you're applying to be a "Teacher". The modern day Educated Philosophers and Intellectuals of the Greco-Roman era. People have to have some pride in their trade and need to push a little more. The practice FTCE/SAE tests I took were far easier than the tests I took at Uni. At the same time I can sympathize with those who failed and the Study Guides should be included in the fee you pay to take the test. Last point I'd like to make is that many states have requirements or strong preferences for teachers to have a masters or take even harder tests. Having to have a Masters in itself is both a far worse financial and educational barrier than a FTCE exam. Florida is far from being the worse in terms of the entry process for becoming a teacher. Just my thoughts.
